## Purpose and philosophy (non-binding)

This section explains the author’s intent. It is **non-binding** and does not replace the enforceable terms in the sections that follow.

The Project was created to:
- showcase the author’s software engineering skills;
- serve as a real, production-grade foundation that the author can use in companies where the author works;
- invite external feedback and contributions from people/teams who can help improve quality, reliability, and features.

What the author wants to encourage:
- learning, experimentation, and peer review;
- constructive feedback, issue reports, and pull requests;
- collaboration with teams that can provide real-world requirements and help improve the Project.

What the author wants to avoid:
- commercial exploitation without permission;
- companies monetizing the Project (directly or indirectly) while removing, hiding, or skipping attribution;
- scenarios where business value is extracted without fair value flowing back to the author (via compensation and/or meaningful contributions).

The author is open to collaboration and learning from other perspectives. However, the author is concerned about scenarios where:
- a company copies the Project;
- uses it to create business value or revenue;
- and fails to provide visible public credit and/or fair value back to the author.

This dual-license is designed to:
- keep non-commercial use accessible (study, experimentation, learning, community review);
- require **explicit authorization** for any company/commercial context;
- make **public attribution mandatory** for any copy, derivative, or deployment;
- allow commercial usage through a direct relationship (email authorization), potentially including compensation (fee/royalties/sponsorship) or a negotiated value exchange (e.g., meaningful upstream contributions).

Why attribution matters:
- The Project is part of the author’s professional portfolio.
- Visible credit protects the author against “invisible adoption” where the author receives none of the reputational value.

Why commercial authorization exists:
- Company usage often creates measurable value (revenue, cost reduction, time savings, competitive advantage).
- Authorization ensures companies do not simply copy the Project and profit from it without a fair arrangement.

If you want to use this Project in a company context, email `sherlott@live.com`—the author’s goal is to find a fair arrangement.

