## 1) Non-Commercial Source-Available License (default)

### 1.1 Grant
Subject to the terms of this license, you are granted a non-exclusive, worldwide, **revocable** right to:
- view and use the source code;
- copy the Project;
- modify the Project and create Derivative Works;
- distribute the Project and Derivative Works.

### 1.2 Non-Commercial restriction
You may **not** use the Project (or Derivative Works) in any way that is directly or indirectly connected to **financial gain** or **commercial advantage**, including but not limited to:
- selling the software;
- offering paid services based on it (consulting, support, hosting, SaaS, etc.);
- using it within or for the benefit of a business/organization where the use is connected to revenue generation, cost reduction, paid operations, or commercial advantage;
- using it as part of a product, internal tool, or workflow in a company/organization when that use is connected to business activity.

### 1.3 Attribution (mandatory) — “give public credit”
Any copy, redistribution, Public Deployment, publication, or Derivative Work must provide **public, visible credit** to the original author.

Required credit:
- Name: **Sherlott**
- Contact: **sherlott@live.com**
- Project name: **Data2Doc**

Minimum placement (choose at least one):
- the README of the derivative repository;
- the product documentation;
- an “About”/credits section in the UI (if applicable).

For **Public Deployments** (including internal dashboards used by multiple people, hosted APIs, SaaS, or tools used in an organization), attribution must be included in at least one of:
- public documentation page;
- API documentation (e.g., Swagger/README) visible to users;
- “About”/credits page; or
- repository/docs that are accessible to the deployment’s stakeholders.

Attribution template (acceptable example):
> “Powered by Data2Doc (c) 2026 Sherlott — sherlott@live.com”

If the Project (or a Derivative Work) is used within a product or service that has public-facing materials (website, docs, sales deck, public API docs), you must ensure the attribution is present in at least one public-facing location. The intent is that users and stakeholders can reasonably discover the origin of the Project.

You must not remove or obscure existing copyright notices.

### 1.3.1 Attribution must be clear
Attribution must be reasonably visible, not hidden behind multiple clicks, and not omitted from distributed artifacts. You may not claim authorship of the original Project.

### 1.4 Distribution conditions
If you distribute the Project or a Derivative Work, you must:
- include this LICENSE file (or a link to it) with your distribution;
- clearly state that your distribution is under the **Non-Commercial** license unless you provide proof of Commercial authorization;
- keep all author attribution visible as required in §1.3;
- not imply endorsement by the author.

### 1.4.1 No removal of credit
You may not remove, hide, or replace the required attribution in any distribution or Public Deployment.

### 1.5 Anti-circumvention
You may not structure your usage to avoid the Commercial Use restrictions (e.g., by routing usage through contractors, affiliates, or “free” tiers) if the overall intent or effect is Commercial.

### 1.6 No trademark rights
This license does not grant you any rights to use the author name, Project name, or trademarks for marketing/branding beyond the attribution required by §1.3.

### 1.7 No warranty / limitation of liability
TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, THE SOFTWARE IS PROVIDED “AS IS”, WITHOUT WARRANTY OF ANY KIND, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE AND NONINFRINGEMENT.

TO THE MAXIMUM EXTENT PERMITTED BY APPLICABLE LAW, IN NO EVENT SHALL THE AUTHOR OR COPYRIGHT HOLDER BE LIABLE FOR ANY CLAIM, DAMAGES OR OTHER LIABILITY, WHETHER IN AN ACTION OF CONTRACT, TORT OR OTHERWISE, ARISING FROM, OUT OF OR IN CONNECTION WITH THE SOFTWARE OR THE USE OR OTHER DEALINGS IN THE SOFTWARE.

