## 4) Practical guidance (examples)

The following examples are guidance only and do not expand the license grant:

Likely **Non-Commercial** (allowed under §1):
- personal study, experiments, and hobby projects not tied to revenue;
- academic work with no paid product/service component;
- internal use at home for personal automation not connected to any business.

Also commonly **Non-Commercial**:
- writing blog posts, tutorials, or public demos that credit the author and do not monetize the Project;
- security research or code review performed privately and reported back;
- running it locally for learning purposes with no business context.

Likely **Commercial** (requires authorization under §2):
- use inside a company (even if not sold) as part of business operations;
- using it to provide consulting/services to clients;
- hosting it as a SaaS/API for users (paid or ad-supported);
- bundling it into a product or distributing it to customers.

Also commonly **Commercial**:
- company “evaluation”, pilot, PoC, internal demo, or benchmarking (even if free), because it is connected to business activity;
- using it as part of work you are paid to do (employment or contract), even if the code itself is not sold;
- using it to generate leads, reduce costs, or gain competitive advantage in an organization;
- training courses, paid workshops, or paid content where the Project is a core deliverable.

Attribution notes:
- If you fork and publish the fork, credit must be visible in the fork’s README and/or documentation.
- If you deploy an API/service using the Project, credit must be reasonably discoverable by stakeholders/users (e.g., docs, API docs, About page).

If unsure, email `sherlott@live.com`.

